column168: WHILE UNLOADING OUTBOUND CITY DELIVERY TRUCKS AT OUR ADAMSBURG, PA. TERMINAL, DOCK EMPLOYEE SET DRUM ON A NAIL WHICH WAS MISSED WHEN REMOVING DUNNAGE AND WHICH PUNCTURED A SMALL HOLE IN THE BOTTOM OF THE 55 GAL DRUM. BY THE TIME LEAK WAS DISCOVERED, SEVERAL GALLONS OF LIQUID HAD LEAKED FROM THE DRUM ONTO THE TRAILER FLOOR.  DRUM WAS PLACED IN AN APPROVED DOT SALVAGE DRUM AND TRAILER FLOOR CLEANED IN ACCORDANCE WITH APPROPRIATE PROCEDURES.

column168: VEHICLE WAS LOADED BY SHIPPER AT HOPEWELL, VA.  4 DRUMS TO A PALLET AND PALLETS SHRINK WRAPPED.  THESE WERE DOUBLE STACKED, EXCEPT FOR THE LAST 2 ROWS.  A BULK HEAD WAS BUILT FOR BRACING OF THE LAST ROW.  MATERIAL USED CONSISTED OF 2X4S, 2X6S AND PLYWOOD.  A NAIL PROTRUDING THROUGH THE MATERIAL WENT INTO ONE OF THE DRUMS.  THERE WAS NO SIGN OF LEAK WHEN DRIVER LEFT ORIGIN.  UPON REACHING GATE TO DESTINATION, DRIVER WAS ALERTED THAT SOMETHING WAS LEAKING FROM THE REAR OF TRAILER.  DRIVER PULLED VEHICLE TO SIDE OUT OF THE TRAFFIC LANES INTO AND OUT OF THE NORFOLK INTERNATIONAL TERMINALS FACILITY.  DRIVER IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED OUR LOCAL OFFICE IN CHESAPEAKE VA AND DISPATCHED A SAFETY CREW TO INCIDENT SITE IN NORFOLK, VA.  SHIPPER PERSONNEL PUMPED OUT REMAINING MATERIAL INTO A NEW DRUM AND PUT DAMAGED DRUM INTO A RECOVERY DRUM.  STAY DRY MATERIAL WAS PUT DOWN IN THE VEHICLE AND ON THE GROUND.  CONTAMINATED MATERIAL WAS SCOOPED UP AND PUT INTO ANOTHER DRUM FOR DISPOSAL.  VEHICLE WAS RETURNED TO ORIGIN OF HOPEWELL VA FOR OFF LOADING AND ADDITIONAL CLEANING.  THE MATERIAL IS A MILD CORROSIVE AND HAD NO ODOR.

SUBSEQUENT CLEAN UP RESULTED IN THE SALVAGING OF ONE CONTAINER AND THE PLACEMENT OF BROKEN MATERIAL, HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCE, CLEAN UP MATERIAL (PROTECTIVE CONVERING, GLOVES), OUTSIDE CONTAINER AND THE REMAINDER OF ABSORBENT SUBSTANCE USED FOR CLEAN UP INTO TWO 5 GALLON DRUMS.  THIS WILL BE SENT TO FEDERAL EXPRESS HEADQUARTERS TO BE DISPOSED OF ACCORDING TO REGULATIONS.

column168: TOW MOTOR WAS UNLOADING LONG PLTS OF FREIGHT OFF STRAIGHT TRUCK.  WHEN MOVING LAST PLT, DRUM WAS LOCATED IN FRONT OF IT, BLADE ON LIFT PUNCTURED BOTTOM OF DRUM.  ONCE INCIDENT WAS REPORTED WHS MEN LAID DRUM ON ITS SIDE TO PREVENT ANY MORE SPILLAGE.  PERSONNEL WERE THEN MOVED AWAY FROM SPILL, DUE TO HARMFUL VAPORS.  SAND WAS USED TO SOAK UP MATERIAL.  TALKED WITH MOTOR OPERATOR, ADVISED HIM TO HAVE SOMEONE LOOK AT WHATS IN FRONT OF PALLET FREIGHT.  ALSO PULL PALLETS BACK BEFORE GOING ALL THE WAY UP.  USED INCIDENT AS EXAMPLE HOW TO PREVENT IN FUTURE.
FORKLIFT BLADE PUNCTURED DRUM AS TRAILER WAS BEING UNLOADED AT DOCK. PRODUCT PLACED IN OVERPACK AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

RECEIVED A CALL FROM PACKAGE CAR DRIVER AT 10:00 A.M.  THE DRIVER STATED THAT THERE WAS A HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PACKAGE LEAKING ON THE FLOOR IN THE BACK.  SUPERVISOR REPORTED TO SCENE AT 11:00 A.M. WITH A FULLY STOCKED SPILL TUB, REMOVED THE PACKAGE AND RETURNED IT TO THE BUILDING FOR DISPOSAL FOLLOWING HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PROCEDURES.  UN-DAMAGED PORTION WILL BE SENT TO THE SHIPPER.  CUSTOMER SERVICE SHOULD VISIT THE SHIPPER AND RETRAIN IN HAZARDOUS MATERIAL PROCEDURES ACCORDING TO UNITED PARCEL SERVICE STANDARDS.  PRELOAD MANAGER/CENTER MANAGER SHOULD PERFORM AUDIT.

THE CONTAINER WAS DISCOVERED LEAKING ONLY WHEN MOVED.  FURTHER INVESTIGATION REVEALED THAT THE SAFETY VENT FRANGIBLE DISC HAD NEVER BEEN INSTALLED.  A DISC WAS INSTALLED AND THE CAR DECONTAMINATED AND RELEASED FOR TRANSPORTATION.

EMPLOYEE WAS MOVING DRUM INTO LOADING TRAILER WITH FORKLIFT.  SPUR OR POINT ON FORK PENETRATED PLASTIC AT DRUM BOTTOM, CAUSING A 1/2" SLIT IN DRUM.  APPROX. 1 PINT OF LIQUID WAS RELEASED ALL OF WHICH WAS SOAKED UP BY CARDBOARD DUNNAGE UNDERNEATH DRUM.  CARDBOARD WAS NEUTRALIZED WITH SODA ASH AND SODA ASH AND CARDBOARD ARE IN SALVAGE DRUM AT THIS FACILITY FOR FUTURE DISPOSAL.  CONTENTS OF DRUM WERE TRANSFERRED TO OVERPACK DRUM AND RETURNED TO SHIPPER.  DAMAGED DRUM ALSO RETURNED TO SHIPPER.

CAR WAS ALLOWED TO CONTINUE ON TO BILLED DESTINATION.

DOCKHAND DROPPED ONE OF THREE BXS IN SHIPMENT WHICH CONSISTED OF FOUR INNER GLASS BOTTLES OF XYLENE COMPOUND.  SUPERVISOR AND ONE OTHER DOCKHAND PLACED BROKEN BOX ON FOUR-WHEEL CART, SHOVED CART INTO EMPTY TRAILER, AND CLOSED ROLL-DOOR ON TRLR.  TRAILER WAS MOVED AWAY FROM DOCK TO CENTER OF EMPTY PARKING AREA.  WHILE APPLYING SAND TO SPILL, ABOVE-MENTIONED DOCKHANDS COMPLAINED OF DIZZINESS, AND SUPERVISOR WAS TEMPORARILY NAUSEOUS AND BRIEFLY LOST CONSCIOUSNESS.  PARAMEDICS WERE SUMMONED AND COUNTY HEALTH ALSO RESPONDED; EMPLOYEES WERE TRANSPORTED TO LOCAL HOSPITAL FOR OXYGEN AND OBSERVATION, AND RELEASED.  SUPERVISOR LOST ONE WORK-DAY; NO LOST TIME FOR DOCKHANDS.  UNION CARBIDE H.E.L.P. RESPONSE TEAM PACKAGED BROKEN BOX INTO AN OVERPACK DRUM, AND DISPOSAL CONTRAOL SERVICE MANIFESTED AND REMOVED THAT DRUM AND CONTENTS TO AN ARIZONA LOCATION FOR FINAL DISPOSAL.  EMPLOYEE MEETINGS WERE CONDUCTED TO REMIND WORKERS THAT NO MATTER HOW FAMILIAR THEY ARE WITH THE FREIGHT, IT ALWAYS REPRESENTS A HAZARD TO THEIR HEALTH. ATTACHED:  M.S.D.S., COPY HAZWASTE MANIFEST.

column168: AT 2200 HRS., ON 11/18/90, TANKER WAS NORTH BOUND AT MILE 100 OF THE DALTON HIGHWAY.  THERE WAS FRESH SNOW ON THE ROADWAY, AND THE DRIVER WAS INVOLVED WITH MEETING A SOUTH BOUND TRUCK.  AT THE POINT OF MEETING, THE NORTH BOUND TRUCK MOVED TOO CLOSE TO THE EDGE OF THE ROADWAY, ALLOWING THE TRAILER TO DRIFT OUT, CAUSING IT TO ROLL ONTO IT'S RIGHT SIDE AND LANDING ON A BOULDER.  THE ROCK PUNCTURED THE CENTER COMPARTMENT OF THE TANKER, AND DAMAGED THE FORWARD COMPARTMENT, ALSO. TRAILER WAS PUMPED OFF, AND BOTH UNITS WERE RIGHTED AND RETURNED TO FAIRBANKS.  AREA WAS CLEANED OF CONTAMINATION, AND PRODUCT WAS USED BY ARCO.

column168: TRACTOR/TRAILER COMBINATION, TRANSPORTING 5,000 GALLONS OF 15% HYDROCHLORIC ACID TO OIL WELL LOCATION, TRAVELING NORTHBOUND ON WEST LOOP 338 ATTEMPTED LEFT HAND TURN ONTO WIRELINE RD. AT UNSAFE SPEED.  VEHICLES OVERTURNED ONTO RIGHT SIDES IN NORTH BAR DITCH RIGHT OF WAY.  THE MANHOLE COVERS REMAINED CLOSED ON TRAILER, HOWEVER MANHOLE COVER CLAMPS HAD NOT BEEN SUFFICIENTLY TIGHTENED RESULTING IN THE LEAKAGE OF 500 GALLONS OUT OF THE TOTAL LOAD OF 5,000 GALLONS WHILE THE VEHICLE WAS OVERTURNED FOR 6 HOURS BEFORE VEHICLE WAS RIGHTED.  AFTER INITIAL EMERGENCY RESPONSE WAS MADE, THE VEHICLES WERE REMOVED FROM THE SCENE AND THE ACID NEUTRALIZED THAT WAS SPILLED.  THE AFFECTED AREA WAS CORDONED OFF UNTIL FOLLOWING DAY, AT WHICH TIME SERVICE FRACTURING COMPANY ARRANGED REMOVAL OF CONTAMINATED SOIL UNDER THE SUPERVISION OF THE TEXAS WATER COMMISSION.

ONE OF OUR 2600 GAL. TANK TRUCKS WAS DELIVERING FUEL TO THE WEIRTON STEEL CORP., WEIRTON, WV.  THE DRIVER WAS UP ON THE RECEIVING TANK AND CONTROLLING THE HOSE NOZZLE WHEN A VITALLIC CONNECTION ON THE UNDERSIDE OF THE TRUCK CAME APART.  THE DRIVER, UPON NOTING THE #2 FUEL ON THE GROUND, IMMEDIATELY SHUT DOWN AND GOT THE LINE TO STOP LEAKING.  HE IMMEDIATELY CONTACTED PLANT SECURITY AND THEN NOTIFIED HIS SUPERVISOR.  THE SUPERVISOR IMMEDIATELY DISPATCHED THE COMPANY'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE TEAM TO THE SCENE. UPON ARRIVAL, THEY FOUND WEIRTON STEEL'S PROPLE IN THE PROCESS OF CONTAINING AND CLEANING UP THE AREA.  SOME SLAG IN THE IMMEDIATE ROAD AREA WAS REPLACED.  THERE WAS NO RUN-OFF AND THINGS WERE WELL IN HAND.  THE TRUCK WAS TAKEN OUT OF SERVICE AND A NEW SUPPLY LINE/FITTING WAS SECURED FRO  FRUEHAUF CORP. AND INSTALLED.

WHEN HE REMOVED THE AIR LINE THE PRESSURE HAD NOT BEEN COMPLETELY RELIEVED AND THE ACID IN THE BOWL SPRAYED OUT.  THE DRIVER GOT A SMALL AMOUNT OF THE SPRAY ON HIM AND HE WAS TREATED AT THE PLANT INFIRMARY.

column168: IT WAS DISCOVERED UPON UNLOADING THAT ONE TOTE TANK IN THE CENTER OF THE TRAILER HAD LEAKED IN TRANSIT.  A 3 FOOT AREA OF THE TRAILER FLOOR WAS SOAKED THROUGH THE PLYWOOD AND DRIPPING UNDERNEATH THE TRAILER.  THE PROBLEM WAS DETERMINED TO BE A FAULTY SEAL AT THE TOP OF THE TOTE ALLOWING THE LIQUID TO LEAK FROM THE TOP.  THE TOTE WAS REMOVED AND CLEANED AND AN OIL ABSORBENT PLACED ON THE SPILL AREA IN THE TRAILER.  THE ABSORBENT WAS SWEPT UP AND DISPOSED OF BY THE RECEIVER.  THE TRAILER WAS ALLOWED TO AIR AND THEN STEAM CLEANED.  THE SHIPPER WAS NOTIFIED OF THE NATURE OF THE CONTAINER FAILURE.  THIS PROBLEM WILL BE LOOKED INTO BEFORE FUTURE LOADS OF THIS TYPE ARE TRANSPORTED.

PUMPING HEATED PRODUCT. NEW DELIVERY HOSE WARMED AND SEPARATED AT THE FITTINGS ATTACHED TO THE PUMP ON THE TRACTOR.  PRODUCT SPILLED ONTO THE REAR OF THE TRACTOR AND INTO THE DESIGNATED CATCH BASIN.  THE SPILL WAS CLEANED UP BY IBM WORLD PERSONNEL AND GARY DYER CONSTRUCTION COMPANY.

THE PUMP LEAKED ON THE TRUCK.  THE DRIVER TURNED THE PUMP OFF AND IT STARTED  TO LEAK MORE.  THE DRIVER THEN PUT NEW GASKET IN THE PUMP AND THEN EVERYTHING WAS OK.  THE DRIVER PUT ABSORBENT ON THE SPILL AND SCOOPED IT INTO A DRUM.

CONTACT WITH THE HIGHWAY SIGN WAS MADE BY THE RIGHT REAR CORNER OF THE CARGO TANK RESULTING IN APUNCTRUE TO THE TANK AT APPROXIMATELY THE THREE O'CLOCK POSTION, WITH THE VEHICLE IN AN UPRIGHT POSTITIO.  WITH THE VEHICLE COMING TO RETS ON ITS RIGHT SIDE, THE HOLE THAT WAS PUNCTRUED IN THE CARGO TANK WAS NOW IN THE SIX O'CLOCK POSTION, CONCEALED BY THE GROUND.  INITIAL REPORTS BY LOCAL AND STATE AUTHORITIES INDICATED THAT MINR LEAKGE HAD OCCURRED DURING THE OVERTURN AND THAT NO LEAKAGE WAS EXPERIENCED OR CONTIUING AFTER THE UNIT CAME TO REST.  A CONTAINEMENT DIKE WAS CREATED WITH A BACKHOE AT THE EAST END OF THE VEHICLE AND THE WEST END WAS CONSIDERED  CONTIANED BY THE NATURAL CONTOUR OF THE GROUND.  LOCAL ANS STATE AUTHORITIES ESTABLISHED A ONE-HALF MILE EVACUATION PERIMATER AROUND THE ACCIDENT SITE, BASED ON INFORMATION CONTIANED IN THE D.O.T.'S EMERGENCY RESPONSE GUIDEBOOK, SHORT TIME AFTER THE ACIDENT OCCURRED.  THIS PERIMATER INVOLVED THE CLOSURE OF I-10, BOTH EASTBOUND AND WESTBOUND. ESSENTAILLY ALL PRODUCT LEAKED OUT OF THE CARGO TANK BEFORE MATERAILS AND EQUIPMENT COULD BE POSITIONED TO TRANSLOAD TO ANOTHER CARGO TANK.  THE BULK OF THE MATERIAL FLOWED BENEATH THE CARGO TANK AND WAS CONCEALED FROM VIEW FOR SEVERAL HOURS.  THE SPILLED MATERIAL THAT FLOWED FROM UNDERNEATH THE CARGO TANK WAS SCONTAINED IN THE IMMEDIATE AREA NAD DID NOT ENTER ANY WATERWASY OR STREAM.  APPROXIMATELY 3,000 GALLONS OF THIS MATERAIL WAS RECOVERD BU PUMP TO ANOTHER CARGO TANK FOR RETURNE TO THE SHIPPER FOR REPROCESSING.  THE OVERTURNED VEHICLE WAS THEN UPRIGHTED AND REMOVED FROMT HE AREA.  CONTAMINATED SOILS WERE SUBSEQUENTLY RECOVERED AND REMOVED AND THE TOP SOIL WAS REPLACED.  THE AREA WAS RESTORED TO ITS NATURAL CONDITION THAT EXISTED PRIOR TO THE ACCIDENT. REPROCESSING OF THE RECOVERD LIQUID MATERIAL WAS DETERMINED BY THE SHIPPER NOT IT BE POSSIBLE.  COMPLAINT DISPOSITION AND DISPOSAL OF THE LIQUID MATERIAL AND THE RECOVERED SOIL WILLBE ACCOMPLISHED FOLLOWING RECEIPT OF THE NECESSAY ANALYTICAL RESULTS.  THE FOUR REPORTED, NON HOSPITALIZED INJURIES REPRESENT RESIDENTIAL EVACUEES THAT RECEIVED MEDICAL OBSERVATION/ TREATMENT AND WERE RELEASED. AT APPROXIMATELY 3:30PM ON 11-21-90, THE EASTBOUND LANES OF I-10 WERE REOPENED AND ALL RESIDENTS WERE ALLOWED TO RETURN TO THEIR HOMES BY THE STATE AND LOCAL OFFICIALS.  EARLIER ON THE MORNING OF 11-21-90, THE WEST BOUND LANES I-10 WERE REOPENED AND SOME NUMBER OF RESIDENTS WERE ALLOWED TO RETURN TO THEIR HOMES BY THE STATE AND LOCAL OFFICIALS. DURING THE RECOVERY AND REMOVAL OF THE CONTAMINATED SOILS, WHICH WAS CONSUCTED SUBSEQUENT TO THE LIFTING OF THE EVACUATION ORDER BY STATE AND LOCAL OFFICIALS, A LIMITED NUMBER OF RESIDENTS LIVING ADJACENT TO THE INCIDENT SITE WERE RELOCATED FOR THEIR COMFORT TO AVOID THEIR CONCERNS OVER POTENTIAL EXPOSURE TO THE MATERIAL. NONE OF THE RELEASED VIALS CONTAINED RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, BUT WHEN THE RELEASED VIALS WERE BEING PLACED BACK IN THE PACKAGE IT WAS OBSERVED THAT SOME OF THE VIALS WHICH REMAINED IN THE PACKAGE WERE LABELED RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL. THE PACKAGE WAS A DOT 7A SPECIFICATION PACKAGE, MARKED RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL, N.O.S. UN2982, AND BORE TWO RADIOACTIVE YELLOW II LABELS INDICATING I-125, 100.8 MBq, AND 0.1 TI.  IT WAS INITIALLY UNCERTAIN IF ANY OF THE RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL CONTENTS HAD BEEN RELEASED FROM THE PACKAGE AND WERE MISSING.  A SEARCH WAS INITIATED FOR ANY MISSING RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL VIALS, AND THE PACKING LIST WAS FOUND.  FROM INFORMATION OBTAINED OFF THE PACKING LIST AND FROM THE SHIPPER IT WAS DETERMINED THAT THE PACKAGE CONTAINED A TOTAL OF 208 VIALS.  EIGHTY-FOUR VIALS EACH CONTAINED 1.2 MBq I-125 FOR A TOTAL ACTIVITY OF 100.8 MBq.  AN INVENTORY WAS MADE OF THE CONTENTS AND IT WAS DETERMINED THAT NONE OF THE 84 VIALS OF RADIOACTIVE MATERIAL HAD BEEN RELEASED FROM THE PACKAGE, AND THAT ALL OF THE NON-RADIOACTIVE VIALS HAD BEEN FOUND.

column168: *23 C. : PUBLIC/PRIVATE PROPERTY DAMAGE:  THE TRUCK CAUSED SOME DAMAGE TO THE MUDDY SHOULDER, BUT WE HAVE NOT BEEN CONTACTED AS TO EXTENT OF THIS DAMAGE OR THE COST OF REPAIR. TODD VEHICLE EASTBOUND ON I-90.  TRAFFIC STOPPED ABRUPTLY, OUR DRIVER SWERVED TO THE RIGHT LANE (FROM THE CENTER LANE) TO AVOID HITTING AN 18 PASSENGER O'HARE BUS.  DRIVER HAD JUST COMPLETED A MIRROR CHECK SO HE KNEW RIGHT LANE WAS VACANT.  TRUCK CROSSED RIGHT LANE AND WENT OVER TO THE SHOULDER.  VEHICLE WAS SKIDDING ON SHOULDER WHEN RIGHT/REAR DUALS SLIPPED OFF OF PAVED SHOULDER AND INTO MUDDY SOIL. THIS CAUSED TRUCK TO PIVOT ON RIGHT STEER TIRE.  TRUCK SLID IN THE MUD UNTIL DRY SOIL WAS HIT, AND THIS CAUSED THE TRUCK TO LAY OVER ON ITS SIDE.  DRIVER WAS WEARING SEAT BELT AND ONLY SUSTAINED A SCRATCH ON HIS ELBOW.  NO OTHER INJURIES.  STATE POLICE, FIRE DEPT., HAZ MAT CREWS WERE SUMMONED.  OUR OWN PEOPLE DID THE CLEAN-UP. HAZ-MAT CREWS WOULDN'T GO INTO BACK OF TRUCK.  MATERIAL SPILLED WAS BASICALLY THE SAME AS BLEACH USED IN THE HOME.  (CHLORINE CHEMICALS FOR SWIMMING POOLS).  DAMAGED FRIEGHT WAS RETURNED TO SHIPPER FOR CLAIM ADJUSTMENT, NEW ORDER WAS SHIPPED OUT THE SAME DAY.  DRIVER WAS DRUG TESTED (NEGATIVE RESULT) AND NOT ALLOWED TO DRIVE UNTIL RESULTS WERE KNOWN.  DRIVER RECEIVED 3 CITATIONS FROM STATE POLICE; COURT DISMISSED ALL 3.

DEFECTIVE HOSE SPLIT SPILLING CHEMICAL.  HOSES WILL BE INSPECTED MORE CLOSELY TO PREVENT THIS FROM HAPPENING AGAIN.

OUR UNIT ARRIVED AT THE QUANTUM CHEMICAL CO., MORRIS, ILLINOIS WITH AN MC-331 TANK TRAILER LOADED WITH PROPYLENE OXIDE WEIGHING 40,840 LBS (NET PAY LOAD) TO PUT INTO CUSTOMERS STORAGE TANK.  THIS TANK IS LOCATED A CONSIDERABLE DISTANCE FROM THE TRACTOR/TRAILER UNLOADING STATION.  THE COMPANY OPERATOR FIGURED THE AMOUNT OF PROPYLENE OXIDE IN OUR TRACTOR/TRAILER TANK, AND THE AMOUNT OF PRODUCT IN THERE STORAGE TANK TO MAKE SURE IT WOULD HOLD ALL THE PRODUCT, AND THEY SAID IT WOULD.  AS STATED THIS STORAGE TANK IS ABOUT 1/2 THE DISTANCE OF A CITY BLOCK FROM THE UNLOADING STATION.  THE COMPANY OPERATOR WENT TO THE STORAGE TANK, AND THE TRANSFER STARTED TAKING PLACE, WITH NITROGEN BEING USED TO PRESSURE THE PRODUCT OFF THE TANK WAGON.  SOON THE COMPANY OPERATOR WAVED TO SHUT OFF THE UNLOADING OPERATION, THE TANK WAS FULL AND APPROXIMATELY 25 GALLONS CAME OUT THE VENT LINE AND INTO THEIR CONCRETE DYKE AROUND THE STORAGE TANK.  THIS DYKE WAS CLOSED OFF IMMEDIATELY AND ALL THE  PRODUCT WAS CONTAINED AND CLEANED UP.  THE BALANCE OF THE PROPYLENE OXIDE THAT WAS LEFT IN OUR TRAILER WAS RETURNED TO THE SHIPPER IN FREEPORT, TEXAS.

TANK CAR ACFX 18679, LOADED WITH ANHYDROUS AMMONIA, WAS DISCOVERED TO BE LEAKING WHILE ENROUTE TO DESTINATION.  THE NEAREST BUREAU OF EXPLOSIVES FIELD INSPECTOR AND BURLINGTON NORTHERN RAILROAD HAZARDOUS MATERIAL TECHNICIAN RESPONDED TO THE REPORTED LEAK AND DETERMINED THAT LADING WAS LEAKING DUE TO A SPLIT RETAINING NUT ON THE OPERATING LEVER OF THE LIQUID EDUCTION VALVE TOWARD THE A END OF THE CAR.  THE LEAK WAS STOPPED BY REPLACING AND TIGHTENING THE VALVE OPERATING LEVER RETAINING NUT BEFORE RELEASING THE CAR FOR MOVEMENT TO DESTINATION.

column168: THIS SHIPMENT WAS DESTINED TO PRESTON TRUCKING COMPANY, DALLAS, TEXAS. TRAILER INSPECTION MADE DUE TO LIQUID LEAKING FROM REAR TRAILER DOORS WHICH WERE PLACARDED CORROSIVE.  THIS TRAILER WAS REMOVED TO THE DESIGNATED "SAFE HAVEN AREA."  THE SHIPPER WAS CONTACTED AND VERIFIED THAT THERE WERE TWO 55 GALLON BARRELS OF POTASSIUM HYDROXIDE IN THE TRAILER EMTCH ENVIRONMETAL SERVICES INC.  WAS CONTACTED TO HANDLE THIS PRODUCT. WHEN THE TRAILER WAS OPENED, THE TWO 55 GALLON BARRELS WERE AT THE REAR TO THE TRAILER.  THE BARREL IN THE CENTER HAD A SMALL HOLE AT THE BOTTOM OF THE INSIDE SEAM.  IT APPEARED THIS DAMAGE OCCURRED WHILE BEING LOADED INTO THE TRAILER AND MAKING CONTACT WITH A PIECE OF METAL AT THE THRESHOLD OF THE TRAILER DOORS.  THE DAMAGED BARREL WAS PLACED INSIDE ANOTHER LARGER BARREL AND RELOADED INTO THE TRAILER.  AN ESTIMATED FIVE OR TEN GALLONS OF THE PRODUCT HAD LEAKED FROM THE BARREL.  NOTHING ELSE IN THE TRAILER WAS DAMAGED BY THIS LEAK.  TRAILER WAS RELEASED AND DELIVERED TO THE CONSIGNEE. SHIPPERS RESPONSIBLITY.

ON NOV 5, 1990 AT APPROX. 8:00AM I ARRIVED AT RIG #119, (MONTEX DRILLING) NOTKNOWING FOR SURE WHICH TANK THEY WANTED ME TO PUMP THE "PREMIUM DIESEL" INTO, ILOCATED THE TOOL PUSHER I.E. FORMAN. HIS NAME IS JEROME. HE THEN TALKED TOCHRIS. THE MUD FOREMAN AND THEY DECIDED IT SHOULD BE PUMPED INTO THE MUD DIESELTANK. I HAD NO WAY OF KNOWING HOW MUCH WAS IN THE TANK AND WE HAVE ALWAYSDEPENDED ON WHAT WE WERE TOLD BY THEM. I BEGAN PUMPING PRODUCT INTO THE TANKAND HAD PUMPED ABOUT 6700 GALLONS INTO THE TANK AT WHICH TIME IT OVERFLOWED.THE SPILL AMOUNTED TO ABOUT 200 GALLONS. THERE ARE SMALL TRENCHES DUG THATDRAIN INTO A LARGE, LINED MUD PIT. WE WERE ABLE TO DRAIN ABOUT 88 PERCENT OFTHE SPILL INTO THE PIT. AT THE TIME OF THE SPILL, I NOTIFIED THE MUD FORMEN ANDHE HELPED DRAIN THE SPILL AS POSSIBLE WE PUMPED SOME OF THE PRODUCT IN THE TANKINTO A MUD/DIESEL MIXING TANK AND I FINISHED UNLADING. AT THAT TIME I CONTACTEDTHE COMPANY PERSON AT THE SITE BY THE NAME OF H.MURPHY.

MR. TOM SEMINOFF OF THERAPEUTIC NUCLIDES & ACCESSORIES, INC. NOTIFIED DR. ROY PARKER, FEDERAL EXPRESS RADIATION PHYSICS CONSULTANT BY TELEPHONE AT 3:14 PM CST ON TUESDAY, NOVEMBER 6, 1990 THAT THEY HAD RECEIVED A RETURNED SHIPMENT FROM ANAHEIM MEMORIAL HOSPITAL ON MONDAY, NOVEMBER 5, 1990 WHICH HAD JUST BEEN OPENED AND SEVEN CESIUM-137 CAPSULES, APPROXIMATELY 199 MILLICURIES, WERE MISSING.  MR. SEMINOFF STATED THAT THEY HAD CONTACTED THE HOSPITAL AND THE HOSPITAL WAS CHECKING TO VERIFY THAT THE CAPSULES HAD BEEN PACKED FOR SHIPMENT.  DR. PARKER TELEPHONED DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRATION IN MEMPHIS AT THE CONCLUSION OF THE ABOVE CONVERSATION AT 3:25 PM CST AND THEY IMMEDIATELY BEGAN TO TRACE THE SHIPMENT TO DETERMINE ITS ACTUAL ROUTING, FEDERAL EXPRESS STATIONS, FACILITIES, VEHICLES AND AIRCRAFT, IF ANY, WHICH MAY HAVE BEEN INVOLVED.  AT 5:01 PM CST THE DIRECTOR OF RADIATION MANAGEMENT FOR THE LOS ANGELES COUNTY DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH SERVICES TELEPHONED DR. PARKER AND REQUESTED AN APPROPRIATE CONTACT AT FEDERAL EXPRESS AND HE REPORTED THE ABOVE DESCRIBED ACTION IN PROGRESS AND THE DIFFICULTY IN IDENTIFYING A SINGLE CONTACT OUTSIDE OF THE DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRATION IN MEMPHIS BECAUSE OF THE UNCERTAINTY AT THE TIME IN THE ROUTING AND THE WORK SCHEDULES OF THE APPROPRIATE MANAGERS.  AT 6:03 PM CST DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRATION REPORTED THAT THEY HAD DETERMINED THAT AN INCIDENT WITH APPARENTLY THE SUBJECT PACKAGE HAD OCCURRED AT THE LAX HUB ON FRIDAY EVENING, NOVEMBER 2, 1990.  AT THE CONCLUSION OF THAT CONVERSATION DR. PARKER TELEPHONED THE DIRECTOR OF RADIATION MANAGEMENT FOR THE LOS ANGELES COUNTY DEPARTMENT OF HEALTH SERVICES A 6:29 PM CST TO REPORT THE PROBABLE SITE OF THE INCIDENT AND IDENTIFIED THE APPROPRIATE MANAGER TO CONTACT.  FEDERAL EXPRESS CORPORATION KNEW THAT THE APPROPRIATE RADIATION EMERGENCY RESPONSE AGENCY HAD BEEN NOTIFIED BEFORE 5:01 PM CST, AND FEDERAL EXPRESS CORPORATION PROVIDED THE RADIATION EMERGENCY RESPONSE AGENCY WITH THE PROBABLE LOCATION OF THE INCIDENT AT THE EARLIEST PRACTICAL MOMENT AFTER CONFIRMATION THAT THE INCIDENT HAD OCCURRED.  FEDERAL EXPRESS CORPORATION DANGEROUS GOODS ADMINISTRATION BRIEFED THE FEDERAL AVIATION ADMINISTRATION ATLANTA CIVIL AVIATION SECURITY OFFICE WEDNESDAY MORNING, NOVEMBER 7, 1990 ON THE STATUS OF THE INCIDENT. column168: TRAILER 15-9302 ENROUTE FROM MIRA LOMA, CA TO ELLENWOOD, GA WAS STOPPED AT KANSAS CITY, MO DUE TO SEEPAGE. JOE DEBNAM OF CHEMTREC, DAVE PELLE OF THE SHIPPER AND E & E WERE CALLED.  SHAW & SONS WERE DISPATCHED TO CLEAN THE SPILL.  THE ABOVE DRUM WAS FOUND TO BE LEAKING AT THE BOTTOM SEAM. THE DRUM WAS PLACED IN A RECOVERY DRUM AND FORWARDED PER THE SHIPPER'S INSTRUCTIONS TO THE CONSIGNEE.  THE SPILL AND THE ABSORBENT MATERIALS WERE CLEANED AND DISPOSED OF BY SHAW & SONS.  THE TRACTOR, 16-7367, AND THE TRAILER, 15-9302, WERE TOWED BY BOOTH'S TOW SERVICE TO ARMADAT AND CLEANED.

column168: TANK CAR GATX 41091, RESIDUE, LAST CONTAINED PHOSPHORIC ACID.  ON 11/07/90, UNION PACIFIC MANAGER OF MECHANICAL MAINTENANCE, KEITH HARMISON AND LOUISIANA STATE POLICE, TRANSPORTATION/ENVIRONMENTAL SAFETY SECTION, LIEUTENANT KENNETH WILLIAMS WERE CONDUCTING NUMEROUS TANK CAR INSPECTIONS. IT WAS OBSERVED THAT GATX 41091 HAD THE MANWAY LID IN THE OPEN POSITION. THE LID OF THE CAR WAS CLOSED BUT NOT SECURED AT THIS TIME.  THE CAR WAS SET OUT AND SENIOR SPECIAL AGENT/HAZARDOUS MATERIAL (SSA/HM) TOM ROBINSON WAS CONTACTED. SSA/HM ROBINSON AND K. HARMISON REINSPECTD THE TANK CAR AND IT WAS OBSERVED THAT NONE OF THE MANWAY LIDS SECURING BOLTS WERE IN PLACE.  THERE WAS NO INDICATION THAT ANY OF THE LIQUID PRODUCT HAD SPILLED AS A RESULT OF THE MANWAY LID BEING OPEN.  SSA/HM ROBINSON PROPERLY SECURED ALL OF THE MANWAY BOLTS.  CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT.  CHEMTREC AND SHIPPER WERE NOTIFIED.

column42: BATTERIES, WET, FILLED WITH ACID, ELECTRIC STORAGE
column168: PASSENGER MR. CHUCK PIGOTT, CHECKED IN HIS BATTERY OPERATED ELECTRIC WHEEL CHAIR AS BAGGAGE FOR FLIGHT 1462.  HE ADVISED THE AGENT THAT HIS WHEEL CHAIR WAS EQUIPPED WITH A DRY CELL BATTERY.  THE EQUIPMENT SERVICE EMPLOYEE (ESE) LOADED THE CHAIR INTO A DC9 CARGO BIN, WHEN HE WAS UNABLE TO STOW IT IN AN UPRIGHT POSITION, HE PROCEEDED TO REMOVE IT FROM THE BIN. WHILE LOWERING IT FROM THE AIRCRAFT BIN ONTO THE RAMP, HE OBSREVED LIQUID SPILLING FROM THE BATTERY, AND AT THE SAME TIME THE CONTAINER AND BATTERY BROKE AWAY FROM THE WHEELCHAIR DROPPING ONTO THE RAMP.  THE SPILLAGE WAS SOAKED UP WITH "QUICK-DRY" MATERIALS WHICH WERE PLACED IN A PLASTIC BOX, AND RETAINED THE BATEERY WAS THEN PLACED INTO A CONTAINER FROM A WHEEL CHAIR BATTERY BOX KIT, AND BOARDED ON THE FLIGHT.  THE AGENT WHO CHECKED IN THE PASSENGER HAS VIEWED THE PASSENGER ELECTRIC WHEELCHAIR VIDEO FOR INSTRUCTION ON PROPER PROCEDURES ON THE FUTURE.

SSA/HM COOPERS' INSPECTION DETERMINED THAT THE GASKET WAS MISSING FROM THE RECESSED AREA IN THE BOTTOM OF THE MAN WAY COVER.  A GASKET WAS FORMED UTILIZING ROUND 3/8 INCH GORTEX MATERIAL AND INSTALLED INTO THE GSAKET FLANGE OF THE MANWAY COVER.  THE COVER PLATE WAS INSTALLED AND SECURED.  CAR WAS THEN MOVED SEVERAL TIMES AND INSPECTED FOR PROPER CONTAINMENT.  NO FURTHER LEAKAGE WAS FOUND AND CAR WAS RELEASED FOR MOVEMENT TO CONSIGNEE.  CHEMTREC WAS NOTIFIED.
